n creation and not part of a library. The SSL handshake feature isn't fully tested yet. We’ve used a public API with no stubs, which leads to questions about whether our custom builder fits into accepted practices. The guidelines suggest we shouldn't create fake replacements for library classes, but since it implements a public interface, it seems alright. Still, the \\\"functional feature\\\" may prefer testing actual behavior. Should I explore if fromBundle(name) throws a NoSuchSslBundleException? Is it functional? Using the default simple request factory with SSL settings seems tricky. Hm, perhaps better asserting no exception is the way to go, but that doesn’t truly confirm usage.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering HTTPS server setup**\\n\\nI’m thinking about using an actual HTTPS server with SslBundle, like com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpsServer, and generating a self-signed certificate. However, creating one through public JDK APIs is tricky without internal access or a BouncyCastle dependency, which I can't use. I wonder if I could embed a PKCS12 keystore as a resource instead. The user mentioned that I should only use the test file, so I might consider putting base64 in a Java string. This would require using the KeyStore API and SSLContext to connect with RestClientSsl. It could be truly functional, but it might be a bit complicated.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring uncovered classes**\\n\\nI’m wondering if there's an existing report that covers the stats for the uncovered classes. This might help to clarify what areas need more attention or improvement. I think it would be beneficial to gather this information to make informed decisions. It seems like the right step to take, as understanding these stats could lead to better strategies moving forward.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_eDZo41tHr25hAI1vhFFIyAOi|fc_026609c108a895f2016a0c9903a4d881968bffff22515f569d", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "stats/org.sp